"Gorodetskaya I.V., Cane M.A., Tremblay L.-B., Kaplan A.","The effects of sea-ice and land-snow concentrations on planetary albedo from the earth radiation budget experiment",2006,"Atmosphere - Ocean","44","2",,"195","205",,,10.3137/ao.440206,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33745598552&partnerID=40&md5=68ab6b365c5c71410509bb16598c0d3a","Lamont-Doherty Earth Observatory, Columbia University, Palisades, NY 10964, United States; Department of Earth and Environmental Science, Columbia University, New York, NY, United States","Gorodetskaya, I.V., Lamont-Doherty Earth Observatory, Columbia University, Palisades, NY 10964, United States, Department of Earth and Environmental Science, Columbia University, New York, NY, United States; Cane, M.A., Lamont-Doherty Earth Observatory, Columbia University, Palisades, NY 10964, United States, Department of Earth and Environmental Science, Columbia University, New York, NY, United States; Tremblay, L.-B., Lamont-Doherty Earth Observatory, Columbia University, Palisades, NY 10964, United States, Department of Earth and Environmental Science, Columbia University, New York, NY, United States; Kaplan, A., Lamont-Doherty Earth Observatory, Columbia University, Palisades, NY 10964, United States","The high-latitude ice/snow-albedo feedback is a principal element in many paleoclimate theories and global warming scenarios. The strength of this feedback is determined by the ice/snow effects on the top-of-atmosphere (TOA) albedo, which is also strongly affected by clouds. Using currently available satellite observations, we estimate the radiative effectiveness (RE) of ice and snow with regards to the TOA albedo, which we define as the change in the TOA albedo corresponding to changes of 0% to 100% in the ice or snow cover. The REs of the northern hemisphere (NH) sea ice, land snow, and southern hemisphere (SH) sea ice are found to be 0.22, 0.23 and 0.16, respectively. This means that, for an incident solar flux of about 400 W m-2 reaching the TOA in the polar latitudes in summer, local reduction in ice/snow concentrations from 100% to 0% will result in a decrease in reflected short wave radiation of approximately 80 W m-2. These changes in the TOA albedo are significant, yet smaller than the associated changes in the surface albedo. Comparison of the TOA albedo values with available surface albedo observations helps to identify the role of clouds in the RE of ice/snow. The analysis is based on the whole time-space domain where the sea ice and land snow appear, and reveals a remarkable similarity in the ice and snow RE in the areas with high sea-ice and land-snow cover variability, despite the varying nature of the surface cover, seasonality, and locations. These estimates provide a useful constraint to test current climate models. © Canadian Meteorological and Oceanographic Society.",,"albedo; radiation budget; radiative forcing; sea ice; shortwave radiation; snow cover; solar radiation; top of atmosphere",,,,,,"Allison, I., Brandt, R.E., Warren, S.G., East Antarctic sea ice: Albedo, thickness distribution, and snow cover (1993) J. Geophys. Res., 98, pp. 12,417-12,429; Armstrong, R.L., Brodzik, M.J., Recent Northern Hemisphere snow extent: A comparison of data derived from visible and microwave satellite sensors (2001) Geophys. Res. Lett., 28, pp. 3673-3676; Barkstrom, B.R., Smith, G.L., The Earth Radiation Budget Experiment: Science and implementation (1986) Rev. Geophys., 24, pp. 379-390; Barkstrom, B.R., Harrison, E., Smith, G., Green, R., Kibler, J., Cess, R., Earth Radiation Budget Experiment (ERBE) archival and April 1985 results (1989) Bull. Am. Meteorol. Soc., 70, pp. 1254-1262. , The ERBE Science Team; Budyko, M.I., The effects of solar radiation on the climate of the earth (1969) Tellus, 21, pp. 611-619; Croll, J., (1875) Climate and Time in Their Geological Relations: A Theory of Secular Changes of the Earth's Climate, p. 577. , Appleton, New York; Curry, J.A., Schramm, J.